---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const pillars = [
  {
    title: "A reactive world that mirrors the player's soul",
    name: "Androlynne",
    href: "#androlynne",
  },
  {
    title: "A government of ghosts",
    name: "The Umbral Plume",
    href: "#umbral-plume",
  },
  {
    title: "A personal, living mirror of the player's morality",
    name: "Lilithyne Nyvashé-Dela",
    href: "#lilithyne",
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title="Featured Examples — Annalisa Ard"
  description="Three pillars of narrative structure: a place, a faction, and a character."
>
  <section class="section cover ex-hero">
    <div
      class="cover-bg"
      style="background-image: url('/images/examples/ai-map-of-kasoltiel-42821b.png');"
    ></div>
    <div class="cover-overlay"></div>
    <div class="ex-hero-inner">
      <p class="eyebrow">Narrative Pillars</p>
      <h1>World Building from the Ground Up</h1>
      <p class="hero-lede">
        Ideas become clearer when shaped with intention. I construct work that
        speaks with purpose, emotion, and deep attention to detail.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section ex-quote">
    <blockquote>
      <p class="quote-text">
        "Why do we tell stories? To try to make sense of a world that can be
        terrifying and enormous."
      </p>
      <footer>
        <p class="quote-attr"><strong>Brennan Lee Mulligan</strong></p>
        <p class="quote-source">Exandria Unlimited: Calamity E.4</p>
      </footer>
    </blockquote>
  </section>

  <section class="section ex-overview">
    <ul class="pillar-list">
      {
        pillars.map((p, i) => (
          <li>
            <a href={p.href}>
              <span class="pillar-num">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, "0")}</span>
              <span class="pillar-title">{p.title}</span>
              <span class="pillar-name">{p.name}</span>
            </a>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>
    <p class="overview-text">
      Drawn from over 400 pages of original lore, the examples here offer
      three glimpses into the living design. Each piece — a place, an
      organization, and a character — is both story and structure; each one
      works as a fragment of its world's greater truth, preserved to show how
      narrative design gives chaos form. From initial sketches to final
      delivery, the goal was to create something both approachable and
      enduring, thoughtful in tone, simple in form, and made to resonate.
    </p>
  </section>

  <article id="androlynne" class="pillar-section pillar-section--bg">
    <div
      class="pillar-bg"
      style="background-image: url('/images/examples/androlynne-1e8cae.jpg');"
    ></div>
    <div class="pillar-inner">
      <header>
        <h2>Androlynne: The Birthplace of Desolation</h2>
        <p class="pillar-meta">
          <strong>Type of Work:</strong> Worldbuilding meets character
          development — a lore-rich demiplane forged through corrupted wish
          magic. This narrative exercise explores the intersection of love,
          loss, and consequence, framed as an environmental storytelling
          prototype.
        </p>
        <p class="pillar-meta">
          <strong>Design Focus:</strong> Emotional consequence, branching
          outcomes, and systemic lore cohesion.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section>
        <h3>Story Overview</h3>
        <p>
          Adventurers find themselves drawn into Kaorol'Tiel, a blighted
          valley in the Dunrock Mountains shrouded in perpetual storm and
          volcanic ash. This cursed land, known to few and survived by even
          fewer, is now ruled by Ryzneuta, a lich lord with unspeakable powers
          no lich ever obtained before. Lured here by ties to Balasar's past
          failings and the lich's murder of Surina, Balasar's friend and
          companion, his adventuring group sets out on a dark course that
          takes them through the many hidden corners and shadowy depths of
          Kaorol'Tiel to see what answers the shadows have hidden in the
          depths of this best-forgotten realm. Kaorol'Tiel is a land of
          ghosts, abyssal demons, and other dark creatures. The wilderness
          hides many secrets, including crumbling ruins and dismal
          battlefields that tell the story of Ryzneuta's life as a conqueror
          and the conquered.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>Androlynne</h3>
        <p>
          Androlynne is a narrative design study set in Kaorol'Tiel, a world
          that mourns itself. Once a thriving refuge for survivors displaced
          across the planes, Androlynne was created by the lich-lord
          Ryzneuta, formerly the knight Evandrin Alterra, whose desperate
          attempt to reunite his scattered family twisted hope into horror.
          The valley's geography, weather, and ecology mirror the corruption
          of its creator: storms pulse with emotional resonance, ruins whisper
          fragmented memories, and even the light bends with regret.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>Narrative Core</h3>
        <p>
          At its heart, the story examines how love can decay into obsession
          and how redemption can curdle into damnation. Evandrin's tragic
          bargain with the glabrezu Rozgat and the sentient weapon known as
          the Blade of Broken Mirrors becomes a class in consequence: every
          noble instinct he once possessed is turned inward until his
          compassion becomes the catalyst for atrocity. His climactic ritual
          — meant to free his child, Elias, from the Astral Sea — instead
          consumes the very souls that gave him hope, transforming him into
          Ryzneuta, the Lord of Desolation, and drowning Androlynne beneath
          necrotic storms of his own making.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>Interactive Design Intent</h3>
        <p>
          The narrative unfolds as a branching, environmental questline where
          players uncover the truth of Androlynne's fall through exploration,
          artifact discovery, and moral choice. Every decision reshapes the
          world's tone and texture; storms quiet when compassion guides the
          player, or surge with renewed fury when power or vengeance takes
          hold. Dialogue, environmental cues, and emergent events are built
          to respond dynamically to emotional alignment, not binary morality,
          allowing players to experience consequence through atmosphere and
          perception rather than exposition.
        </p>
        <p>
          The most defining feature of this design is the dual-reality
          system, which unlocks divergent layers of truth once a player opens
          the door to corruption. I developed two intersecting narrative
          frameworks: one grounded in objective reality, and another filtered
          through a corrupted consciousness. Each presents altered lore
          fragments, contradictory NPC memories, and distorted world details
          — creating a psychological feedback loop that makes players
          question what is real, who can be trusted, and whether redemption
          is possible at all. As players compare experiences, they become
          both participants and unreliable narrators in the same world,
          mirroring the central theme of Androlynne itself: that perception,
          like hope, is fragile — and easily broken.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>Design Goals</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Build a reactive world simulation where geography, weather, and
            lore dynamically mirror player behavior and emotional state.
          </li>
          <li>
            Integrate environmental storytelling to replace exposition with
            experiential discovery.
          </li>
          <li>
            Weave branching quests around thematic polarity (hope vs.
            despair, redemption vs. obsession) to give narrative weight to
            gameplay decisions.
          </li>
          <li>
            Design lore fragments and NPC interactions that reveal different
            facets of truth depending on player empathy, curiosity, or
            ambition.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>Narrative Significance</h3>
        <p>
          Androlynne exemplifies my approach to narrative design: story as
          ecosystem. Every decision — visual, emotional, or systemic —
          supports the player's journey and makes it unique to each outlook,
          and each player. By binding worldbuilding to emotional architecture,
          the project transforms traditional lore into a living reflection of
          choice, ensuring that the environment itself becomes both witness
          and judge of the player's actions.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </article>

  <article id="umbral-plume" class="pillar-section pillar-section--bg pillar-section--right">
    <div
      class="pillar-bg pillar-bg--right"
      style="background-image: url('/images/examples/umbral-plume-contrast-1fa291.png');"
    ></div>
    <div class="pillar-inner pillar-inner--narrow">
      <header>
        <h2>The Umbral Plume: Shadow Society in Shadowed Lands</h2>
        <p class="pillar-meta">
          <strong>Type of Work:</strong> Faction design & narrative systems
          integration — an invisible order that shapes the world's fate,
          reflecting not who holds power, but who controls the truth.
        </p>
        <p class="pillar-meta">
          <strong>Design Focus:</strong> Moral complexity, world reactivity,
          and information as power.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section>
        <h3>Story Overview</h3>
        <p>
          In the fractured nation of Xhorhas, where survival favors the
          ruthless, the Umbral Plume thrives in silence. Born from the chaos
          following the Calamity, it grew from a coalition of spies,
          merchants, and mages who believed that civilization could only be
          protected by those willing to operate unseen. While kingdoms
          fought in the light, the Umbral Plume rewove the world's fate in
          the dark — manipulating trade routes, forging secret pacts, and
          erasing truths that threatened "balance."
        </p>
        <p>
          Their credo is simple: "Control is compassion." They see themselves
          not as villains but as custodians of order — the quiet architects
          preventing the next catastrophe. Yet within their ranks, ambition
          and ideology clash; every cell guards a fragment of the truth,
          ensuring that no one, not even their enigmatic leader known only
          as the Shadow, ever sees the full design.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>Narrative Core</h3>
        <p>
          The Umbral Plume examines how the pursuit of order corrodes the
          soul. Its stories revolve around ethical dissonance — when the only
          way to preserve peace is through deceit. The faction serves as a
          mirror to the player's own rationalizations: every collaboration,
          every betrayal, forces a reckoning between belief and consequence.
        </p>
        <p class="quote-question">
          At its heart lies the question: <em>If control prevents chaos, can
            it ever be innocent?</em>
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>Interactive Design Intent</h3>
        <p>
          Faction interaction is built on a reputation-through-behavior
          system, where trust is earned not by declared loyalty but by
          consistent action. The Umbral Plume observes the player from the
          shadows, adapting its responses to how secrets are used, shared,
          or withheld.
        </p>
        <p>Information functions as both resource and weapon:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Sharing intelligence opens new paths but alters the balance of
            power elsewhere.
          </li>
          <li>
            Concealment preserves independence but closes strategic
            opportunities.
          </li>
          <li>
            Manipulating both sides risks exposure, triggering dynamic
            betrayal events that rewrite alliances mid-campaign.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          To embody the organization's mystique, I designed a layered
          knowledge framework — multiple simultaneous "truths" coexisting
          across questlines. Each character perceives events differently
          depending on what information the player controls, creating a world
          of information asymmetry where knowledge defines reality. Players
          become unreliable narrators in their own story, unsure whether they
          are using the Umbral Plume or being used by it.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>Design Goals</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Develop a morally gray faction system that measures influence
            through perception, not numeric alignment.
          </li>
          <li>
            Implement information-economy mechanics, turning secrets into
            tradable resources with emotional cost.
          </li>
          <li>
            Integrate branching espionage quests whose outcomes reverberate
            across political and personal storylines.
          </li>
          <li>
            Reinforce faction ideology through visual and environmental
            motifs — architecture, lighting, and sound shifting with secrecy
            or exposure.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>Narrative Significance</h3>
        <p>
          The Umbral Plume showcases my ability to design narrative
          ecosystems of influence — where control, secrecy, and consequence
          intertwine. It complements Androlynne by shifting the lens from
          personal tragedy to collective manipulation, demonstrating
          versatility across emotional, systemic, and philosophical
          storytelling.
        </p>
        <p>
          Here, the story is not about a world reacting to the player's
          soul, but about a player navigating a world that reacts to what
          they choose to reveal. It's a study in the art of unseen hands —
          how hidden systems and moral compromise can drive the deepest kind
          of reactivity: the one that happens inside the player.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </article>

  <article id="lilithyne" class="pillar-section pillar-section--purple">
    <div class="pillar-grid">
      <div class="pillar-text">
        <header>
          <h2>Lilithyne Nyvashé-Dela: The Shadow That Chose the Light</h2>
          <p class="pillar-meta">
            <strong>Type of Work:</strong> Character design & narrative
            architecture — a soul forged by betrayal, where survival means
            choosing which parts of yourself to keep alive.
          </p>
          <p class="pillar-meta">
            <strong>Design Focus:</strong> Moral consequence, identity
            systems, and emotionally reactive storytelling.
          </p>
        </header>

        <section>
          <h3>Character Overview</h3>
          <p>
            Born Melinoë Tenebranox, heir to a dynasty of power and cruelty,
            Lilithyne carries the weight of a legacy built on blood and
            manipulation. Her family's empire of spies and sorcerers defined
            strength as dominance and affection as weakness. When her sister,
            Ephra, murdered their mother to seize control, Melinoë's final
            illusion of loyalty shattered. She disappeared into the wide world
            and was reborn as Lilithyne Nyvashé-Dela: a fugitive who refuses
            to inherit her family's darkness but can never fully escape it.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h3>Narrative Core</h3>
          <p>
            Lilithyne's story explores what it means to reject destiny
            without erasing it. Every interaction with her revolves around
            identity and trust: how much of her former self she admits, how
            much she conceals, and whether the player encourages her to
            confront or bury her past. Her arc is designed as a mirror
            narrative so the player's choices influence not only her
            perception of the world but her self-definition. Compassion
            pushes her toward redemption; pragmatism strengthens her resolve
            as a survivor; cruelty reawakens the Tenebranox blood she's tried
            to deny.
          </p>
          <p class="quote-question">
            <strong>Core Question:</strong> <em>Can someone born in darkness
              ever use those shadows to do good?</em>
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h3>Interactive Design Intent</h3>
          <p>
            Lilithyne's presence in the game functions as both companion and
            narrative catalyst. Her loyalty system is built on behavioral
            empathy rather than dialogue approval.
          </p>
          <p>
            When the player chooses mercy in tense situations, her demeanor
            softens; she offers new dialogue revealing vulnerability and
            fear. When the player deceives, manipulates, or justifies
            ruthless choices, she responds with recognition and guarded
            respect, unlocking new tactical or espionage options drawn from
            her Tenebranox heritage.
          </p>
          <p>
            At the story's midpoint, the player may choose to help her
            confront or conceal her true identity. This choice permanently
            alters her visual presentation, combat style, and dialogue
            delivery, embodying the theme of identity as agency.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h3>Design Goals</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Craft a character-driven questline exploring trauma,
              redemption, and moral adaptability.
            </li>
            <li>
              Implement behavior-based emotional reactivity rather than
              binary approval systems.
            </li>
            <li>
              Blend personal narrative with gameplay stakes, ensuring story
              choices impact mechanics.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h3>Narrative Significance</h3>
          <p>
            Lilithyne Nyvashé-Dela exemplifies my approach to
            character-centric systems design: story and mechanics evolving
            together to evoke empathy, tension, and consequence. Her arc
            demonstrates how identity can function as both narrative and
            system; something that changes not through exposition but through
            the player's behavior.
          </p>
          <p>
            She stands as a counterpoint to Androlynne's tragic world and
            The Umbral Plume's political manipulation: where those stories
            explore corruption on a cosmic or societal scale, Lilithyne's is
            intimate, human, and deeply personal. In her, the storm is
            internal, but no less reactive.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>
      <aside class="pillar-portraits">
        <img
          src="/images/examples/lilithyne-tenebranox-dbf255.jpg"
          alt="Lilithyne portrait"
          loading="lazy"
        />
        <img
          src="/images/examples/lilithyne-tenebranox-scene-a72003.jpg"
          alt="Lilithyne scene"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </aside>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .ex-hero {
    min-height: 70vh;
    text-align: left;
    justify-content: flex-start;
    align-items: flex-end;
    padding-bottom: 6vh;
  }
  .ex-hero-inner {
    max-width: 800px;
    text-align: left;
  }
  .eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.1em;
    color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.85);
    margin: 0 0 0.6em;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
  }
  .ex-hero h1 {
    margin-bottom: 0.5em;
  }
  .hero-lede {
    font-size: 1.3em;
    max-width: 32em;
    color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.92);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .ex-quote {
    padding: 8vh 5%;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .ex-quote blockquote {
    margin: 0 auto;
    max-width: 1100px;
  }
  .quote-text {
    font-size: 2.5em;
    line-height: 1.3;
    font-style: italic;
    margin-bottom: 1.2em;
    font-weight: 400;
  }
  .quote-attr {
    font-size: 1.5em;
    margin: 0;
    font-weight: 700;
  }
  .quote-source {
    font-size: 1.1em;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin: 0.2em 0 0;
    font-weight: 300;
  }

  .ex-overview {
    padding: 4vh 5%;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1.2fr 1fr;
    gap: 4rem;
    align-items: start;
    max-width: 1400px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  .pillar-list {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: grid;
    gap: 1.5em;
  }
  .pillar-list a {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 3rem 1fr;
    grid-template-rows: auto auto;
    gap: 0.1em 1rem;
    padding: 1em 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    color: inherit;
  }
  .pillar-list a:hover .pillar-title,
  .pillar-list a:hover .pillar-name {
    color: var(--accent);
  }
  .pillar-num {
    grid-row: 1 / span 2;
    align-self: center;
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.5em;
    color: var(--accent);
  }
  .pillar-title {
    font-size: 1.4em;
    font-weight: 700;
    line-height: 1.3;
  }
  .pillar-name {
    font-size: 1.05em;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-style: italic;
  }
  .overview-text {
    font-size: 1.2em;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .pillar-section {
    position: relative;
    padding: 10vh 5%;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .pillar-section--bg .pillar-bg {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background-size: cover;
    background-position: center;
    background-attachment: fixed;
    opacity: 0.55;
    z-index: 0;
  }
  .pillar-bg--right {
    background-position: right center;
  }
  .pillar-section::before {
    content: "";
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: linear-gradient(
      to bottom,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.85),
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.6) 50%,
      rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.85)
    );
    z-index: 1;
  }
  .pillar-inner {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 2;
    max-width: 880px;
  }
  .pillar-inner--narrow {
    max-width: 760px;
  }
  .pillar-section--right .pillar-inner {
    margin-left: 0;
  }
  .pillar-section h2 {
    font-size: 2.5em;
    margin-bottom: 0.5em;
  }
  .pillar-meta {
    font-size: 1.15em;
    color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.88);
    margin: 0 0 0.7em;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
  .pillar-section section {
    margin-top: 2.2em;
  }
  .pillar-section h3 {
    font-size: 1.3em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--accent);
    margin: 0 0 0.6em;
  }
  .pillar-section p {
    font-size: 1.08em;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  .pillar-section ul {
    padding-left: 1.4rem;
  }
  .pillar-section ul li {
    margin-bottom: 0.5em;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }
  .quote-question {
    font-size: 1.2em !important;
    padding-left: 1em;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--accent);
    color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.92);
  }

  .pillar-section--purple {
    background: rgba(18, 0, 32, 1);
  }
  .pillar-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr;
    gap: 4rem;
    max-width: 1400px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    align-items: start;
    position: relative;
    z-index: 2;
  }
  .pillar-portraits {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 2rem;
    position: sticky;
    top: 2rem;
  }
  .pillar-portraits img {
    width: 100%;
    border-radius: 0.3em;
    aspect-ratio: 1 / 1;
    object-fit: cover;
  }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .ex-overview {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
    .pillar-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
    .pillar-portraits {
      position: static;
      flex-direction: row;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
    }
    .pillar-portraits img {
      flex: 1 1 200px;
    }
    .pillar-section h2 {
      font-size: 1.8em;
    }
    .quote-text {
      font-size: 1.7em;
    }
  }
</style>
